arwickshire), though this last may be a manorial placename deriving from the surname. The Herefordshire placenames probably derive from Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Welshman’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. The Shropshire placename derives from Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + <i>ford</i>. If it does not derive from the surname, the Warwickshire placename probably has the same etymology as the Herefordshire placenames.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Walford in Wimborne Minster (Dorset). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>walt</i> ‘unsteady’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Walter De Walford was born in 1291, in Walford, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Walter De Walford in 1311, in Walford, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons."},"et":{"1291–":"1291–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1313–Male":"1313–Surnud","1315–1327":"1315–1327","1317–1327":"1317–1327","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1321–1319":"1321–1319","1291–Female":"1291–Surnud","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1313":"1313","1311":"1311","1321":"1321","1319":"1319","1291":"1291","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Walford, Shropshire, England":"Walford, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1291–":